Two items, each with a genuinely multi-line element. Elements no longer paren-
wrap merely for being on a wide line (see internal/printer's breakWideLiterals
wiring), so this case uses elements that are themselves multi-line to keep
exercising the paren shape.

A multi-line element reaches gofmt as a single-rune placeholder handed to
breakWideLiterals as its forceMarker: its true width is unknowable and it can
never be a one-liner, so a literal holding it PACKED is over budget without
measuring. Each item therefore breaks its fields one per line AND paren-wraps its
element — so each item becomes its own gofmt alignment section, and the
cross-item alignment that historically (#62) let `page` gain a stray alignment
cell on re-format no longer even exists.

Re-formatting fmt's own output must not drift: the decorative paren still puts the
element alone on its line, and goexprshape.Sanitize's before-hole collapse
(guarded directly by TestSanitizeBeforeCollapseIsParenOnly in
internal/goexprshape/shape_test.go) is still the fix for the single-pass artifact
that shape once caused. This case pins that a two-item literal whose fields break
and whose elements paren-wrap formats and reformats without drifting.

-- input.gsx --
package ui

var nav = []item{
	{label: "Team View", icon: <UsersIcon>
		<title>users</title>
	</UsersIcon>, page: TeamViewPage{}, pathMatch: "/team"},
	{label: "Search", icon: <SearchIcon>
		<title>search</title>
	</SearchIcon>, page: ListPage{}, pathMatch: "/list/"},
}
-- fmt.golden --
package ui

var nav = []item{
	{
		label:     "Team View",
		icon:      (
			<UsersIcon>
				<title>users</title>
			</UsersIcon>
		),
		page:      TeamViewPage{},
		pathMatch: "/team",
	},
	{
		label:     "Search",
		icon:      (
			<SearchIcon>
				<title>search</title>
			</SearchIcon>
		),
		page:      ListPage{},
		pathMatch: "/list/",
	},
}
